"instruction": "Load 'metric.csv'. Compute the global P95 of 'value' for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series (no time filtering). Then filter metric records to the incident window 2024-02-24 05:03:03 UTC through 2024-02-24 05:33:03 UTC (inclusive). For only the candidate services: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service, compute per (cmdb_id, kpi_name): count_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC or NaT), max_value_in_window, and p95. Return this compact table (limit to 50 rows) sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc. Also return the number of candidate services that have any anomaly_count>0."
}

{
"analysis": "We found widespread socket anomalies concentrated on many *-mongo components (anomaly_count=25 across the window) and memory (mem) spikes in several services including all five candidate services (each candidate shows mem anomalies, anomaly_count=2). This suggests a systemic connection/socket-level problem affecting DBs, while candidate services are also showing elevated memory/latency points. To decide which candidate service is the root cause we must use trace data to see which candidate is the downstream faulty service in the call chains (or which candidate shows trace-level anomalies such as increased duration) during the incident window. Traces will help identify the most downstream faulty candidate among multiple service-level anomalies.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Load 'trace.csv'. Compute the global P95 of 'value' for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series (no time filtering). Then filter trace records to the incident window 2024-02-24 05:03:03 UTC through 2024-02-24 05:33:03 UTC (inclusive). For only the candidate services: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service, compute per (cmdb_id, trace_name): count_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC or NaT), max_value_in_window, and p95. Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, and also return the number of candidate services that have any anomaly_count>0 and the list of unique trace_name values seen for these candidates in-window."
}

{
"analysis": "Metrics analysis found widespread socket anomalies on many *-mongo components during the incident window and memory (mem) spikes in all five candidate services (each candidate had 2 mem anomaly points). Trace-level anomaly scanning flagged many error_rate traces for the candidate services, but these are likely noisy because many trace error_rate P95 values equal 0.0 (so value >= P95 marks zeros as anomalies) and do not reliably indicate which service is the root cause. Given multiple candidate services show mem anomalies and trace error_rate is unhelpful, the next step is log analysis to confirm whether any of the candidate services show socket/socket-connection errors or other error messages during the incident window that point to the failure reason (e.g., socket error). We should therefore examine both aggregated normalized log features (log.csv) for candidate services in the incident window and actual error messages from error_logs.csv filtered to the candidate services and the incident window. This will help decide which candidate service is the most likely root-cause component and whether the failure reason is a socket error or something else.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Load 'log.csv' and 'error_logs.csv'. For the candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) within the incident window 2024-02-24 05:03:03 UTC to 2024-02-24 05:33:03 UTC (inclusive):\n1) From log.csv: for each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute count_in_window (rows), sum_value_in_window (sum of 'value'), max_value_in_window, and earliest_timestamp_where_value_gt_0 (UTC or NaT). Return a compact table sorted by sum_value_in_window desc limited to top 20 rows.\n2) From error_logs.csv: filter rows to the same candidate services and incident window; return total count of error log rows and the top 10 distinct (message, cmdb_id) combinations with their earliest occurrence timestamp (UTC) and counts, limited to 10 rows. Ensure timestamps are returned in UTC."
}

